1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
c3 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 
15. Re4 {This move looks very random, but understanding it and the ideas behind 
it and Black's reply will help you make sense of why people do what in the 
Marshall. As for the relevance of 15. Re4, play is sharp, but Black is OK 
without being down to only moves, so I don't expect Re4 to come back into 
fashion anytime soon. So, White wants to go Rh4 and push our Queen back. What to 
do?} g5 {Stopping Rh4 using a little tactic. The pawn might also assist a quick 
attack in the form of *f5-f4.*} 16. Qf1 {The most testing move, cowardly 
offering a queen exchange.} Qh6 $5 {Another fresh move that will a) hopefully 
surprise opponents b) save us time from studying the well-explored Qh5 c) stand 
the test of time. There is nothing wrong with Qh5 either, after Nd5 all three of 
Bh3 Bf5 and f5 work AFAIK, making Re4 a very odd choice for White. The queen on 
h6 sidesteps the exchange, covers g5 and is not as vulnerable to Bd1 harassment 
as it would be on h5. d6 being defended can come in handy as well.} 17. Re1 
{[%cal Gf7f5] Prophylaxis against f5 seems most prudent.} Nf4 $1 {Daring White 
to take the horse. One capture leads to trouble, one to rough equality.} 18. 
gxf4 $2 gxf4 {[%cal Bg8h8,Bf8g8,Bc8h3][%csl Rg2] You know the drill: Kh8, Rg8, 
Bh3, *Rg7-Rag8* if needed. White is lost.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Marshall 15. Be3 #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825651"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
c3 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 
15. Be3 {Arguably the most natural move, White just continues developing. This 
move was the subject of hot debates throughout the 80s, 90s, and 2000s, but I 
would not expect to see much of it anymore. Engines aren't too scared of it...} 
Ra7 $5 {[%cal Ba7e7] A rare idea, courtesy of LeelaZero (and GM Jan Plachetka!) 
There is nothing wrong with the old main lines starting with 15... Bg4, but they 
do require Black to learn quite some theory in order to hold. Let's get our own 
surprise in first! The rook is headed for e7, where it will team up with his 
f8-colleague (often headed to e8) to put pressure at the white construction, 
especially the bishop on e3. Note that the f8-rook has another possible 
function, staying where it is to support f5-f4. Sure, the a8-rook could get to 
e8 in one go after 15... Bg4 16. Qd3, but it would still take 2 moves to get to 
e7. Ra7 is arguing that R to e7 always makes sense, while Bg4 doesnt, that 
bishop might have a bright future on b7 or even on c8. The key to this move 
being good is the very typical Marshall-theme that Black is not afraid of Bxd5 
in most scenarios. We will see why in this and the following files.} 16. Nd2 Bg4 
$1 {[%cal Rd1d3,Rd3f1] Only now that the Queen no longer has access to the d3-f1 
route.} 17. Qc2 Bf5 18. Qc1 Re7 19. Bg5 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 h6 21. Be3 Bd3 {It is 
surprisingly hard for White to untangle, but surprisingly easy to lose in one 
move!} 22. Qd1 $2 Nxe3 23. fxe3 Bxg3 24. hxg3 Qxg3+ {[%csl Rg1]} 25. Kh1 Qh3+ 
26. Kg1 Qxe3+ {[%cal Bd3e2,Bf8e8] White is lost.} *

