[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Marshall 14. Qf3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825650"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
c3 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4][%csl Re4] This 
looks humble and, frankly, a bit dumb. Why would this move be better than 12. 
d4? It does cover e4, but other than that it pales in comparison. It turns out 
that covering e4 is pretty important. Let's face it, 12. d3 has become the main 
challenge to the Marshall. It is the Thanos to 12. d4's Loki, or the Joker to 
12. d4's Mr.Freeze if you are a DC guy. And we aren't talking the fun-loving 
Jack Nicholson type Joker either - this is the buzzkill Joaquin Phoenix version. 
Few winning chances for Black, defending some dry slightly worse symmetrical 
positions or endings a pawn down - a typical 55%-45% line. All of this is at the 
highest levels, of course. It's not exactly a secret, either - my database shows 
27 12. d3 games to 2 12. d4s in games between 2700 players since 2016 (yep, my 
database is weird) . Now to the good news: I have two lines that I believe are 
perfectly fine for Black. In this chapter, we will cover early alternatives and 
then my personal favorite, the move 14... Re8. I consider this a better 
practical choice. Next, we will learn the mainline 14... Qh4 (don't get used to 
me giving you choices!)} Bd6 13. Re1 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Rd3] The way to go - Black 
just develops a piece while targeting the pawn on d3.} 14. Qf3 {The only 
critical move, the Queen targets the bishop and keeps an eye on d3, preparing 
Nd2. Be aware that 14. Nd2 exists, its main aim is to force a draw. And 
admittedly, it will probably succeed... After 14. Qf3, Black faces a big 
decision. Qh4, Qf6, Re8, and Bg6 have all been played at a high level. If you 
can find a line to your liking here can and should determine if you want to 
include the Marshall into your repertoire. Personally, I am still happy to go 
14... Re8 here. Let me show you why!} Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge8e1][%csl Re1] My weapon 
of choice. We threaten mate in 1 and try to use the temporary weakness of the 
e1-square. It leads to very sharp play where White has to walk a minefield of 
only-moves if he wants to prove an edge. Even if he does, I do believe Black is 
OK, so I would (naively?) be ready to play it tomorrow even though I have played 
and recommended it before. As a surprise, it gains in strength, of course.} 15. 
Rxe8+ Qxe8 {[%cal Ge8e1][%csl Re1] No points for finding this one.} 16. Nd2 
{[%cal Bd2f1] The critical test, the knight is headed to f1.} Qe1+ {Not just to 
give a check, but also stopping Ne4 and making it hard for White to develop the 
queenside. Let the games begin!} 17. Nf1 {[%csl Rf5] 5 points.} Bg6 $1 {Better 
than e.g. g6, after which the bishop can be targeted with g4.} 18. Bc2 $4 {This 
was played in Karjakin-Svidler (World Cup final blitz 2015), but it loses to:} 
Nxc3 {[%csl Rc3,Rc2,Ra1]} 19. bxc3 Qxc3 {[%cal Gc3a1,Bc3c2][%csl Rc2,Ra1]} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Marshall 8. h3 #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825640"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
h3 Bb7 $1 9. d3 d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 {Last and least, we will look at some ways for 
White to cowardly turn the pawn on e5 down. It is understandable that White 
players would look in these directions, as not everybody is comfortable 
relinquishing the initiative with White after just 11 moves in order to grab a 
pawn. Most of these cases have started to look at other moves than 8. h3 though, 
theoretically, there is nothing too scary lurking here.} 11. Nbd2 {This move 
used to be a bit of a headache until black players, inspired by Aronian, noticed 
they can just ignore defending the e5-pawn.} Qd7 $1 12. Nxe5 $2 {Of course the 
critical test, but not a good move. This move has a very curious history that we 
will unpack over the next couple of moves. I first came across this line while 
watching the Candidate's tournament game Anand-Aronian, 2014. A game won by 
Anand by the way, who went on to win the tournament convincingly. Who knows how 
chess history might have gone had Aronian played a different 13th move?} Nxe5 
13. Rxe5 Nf4 $1 {An obvious improvement over Aronian's 13... Nf6. Obvious if you 
know the next move, that is...} 14. Ne4 Ng6 {[%csl Re5] Traps the rook.} *

