chess history might have gone had Aronian played a different 13th move?} Nxe5 
13. Rxe5 Nf4 $1 {An obvious improvement over Aronian's 13... Nf6. Obvious if you 
know the next move, that is...} 14. Nf3 Nxg2 $1 {[%csl Rg2] Boom. Black has a 
serious attack, White is in big trouble. This move was an open secret for quite 
a while. More open than secret. French GM Romain Edouard mentioned it on 
Facebook shortly after the game Anand-Aronian. Then Anish Giri gave this move in 
his notes for New in Chess. This is where yours truly learned about it, who then 
went on to play it in a Bundesliga game in late 2014... Expertly drawing a 
winning position, of course. So far, so good. With all that history, the 
surprise was great when this position reappeared on the highest level in 
Ivanchuk-So, Wijk 2015, giving So one of his easier black victories. I can 
understand Ivanchuk missed Romain's Facebook post or didn't study that issue of 
NiC. But ignoring my board 8 games in the Bundesliga is just asking for trouble. 
OK, back to chess, why exactly should Black give that knight?} 15. Kxg2 a5 $1 
{[%cal Ga5a4,Ba8a6,Ba6g6] The point. I like a good multipurpose move and this 
one is up there. The dual-threat of ...a4 and *Ra6-Rg6* or Rf6 cannot be met 
successfully.} 16. c3 Ra6 17. d4 {This might be the most resilient, but great it 
is not.} Rg6+ 18. Kh2 Bd6 {[%cal Bd6h2][%csl Rh2,Re5]} 19. Nh4 a4 $1 {[%csl 
Rb3]} 20. Nxg6 hxg6 {[%cal Gf7f6]} 21. Qg4 Qxg4 22. hxg4 axb3 {[%cal 
Gf7f6,Bd6e5] After some great play by both sides, we reach an endgame that only 
Black can win.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
