[White "Anti-Marshall 8. h3 #3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825642"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
h3 Bb7 $1 9. d3 d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 {Last and least, we will look at some ways for 
White to cowardly turn the pawn on e5 down. It is understandable that White 
players would look in these directions, as not everybody is comfortable 
relinquishing the initiative with White after just 11 moves in order to grab a 
pawn. Most of these cases have started to look at other moves than 8. h3 though, 
theoretically, there is nothing too scary lurking here.} 11. Nbd2 {This move 
used to be a bit of a headache until black players, inspired by Aronian, noticed 
they can just ignore defending the e5-pawn.} Qd7 $1 12. Nxe5 $2 {Of course the 
critical test, but not a good move. This move has a very curious history that we 
will unpack over the next couple of moves. I first came across this line while 
watching the Candidate's tournament game Anand-Aronian, 2014. A game won by 
Anand by the way, who went on to win the tournament convincingly. Who knows how 
chess history might have gone had Aronian played a different 13th move?} Nxe5 
13. Rxe5 Nf4 $1 {An obvious improvement over Aronian's 13... Nf6. Obvious if you 
know the next move, that is...} 14. Nf3 Nxg2 $1 {Boom. Black has a serious 
attack, White is in big trouble. This move was an open secret for quite a while. 
More open than secret. French GM Romain Edouard mentioned it on Facebook shortly 
after the game Anand-Aronian. Then Anish Giri gave this move in his notes for 
New in Chess. This is where yours truly learned about it, who then went on to 
play it in a Bundesliga game in late 2014... Expertly drawing a winning 
position, of course. So far, so good. With all that history, the surprise was 
great when this position reappeared on the highest level in Ivanchuk-So, Wijk 
2015, giving So one of his easier black victories. I can understand Ivanchuk 
missed Romain's Facebook post or didn't study that issue of NiC. But ignoring my 
board 8 games in the Bundesliga is just asking for trouble. OK, back to chess, 
why exactly should Black give that knight?} 15. Kxg2 a5 $1 {The point. I like a 
good multipurpose move and this one is up there. The dual-threat of ...a4 and 
*Ra6-Rg6* or Rf6 cannot be met successfully.} 16. c3 Ra6 17. d4 {This might be 
the most resilient, but great it is not.} Rg6+ 18. Kh2 Bd6 19. Nh4 a4 $1 20. Bc2 
f6 {Black should win.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Marshall 8. a4 #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825644"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
a4 {We meet another member of the trifecta of evil trying to undermine our faith 
in the Marshall. 8. c3 followed by 12. d3 and 6. d3 are the other members of 
that club. 8. a4 is a logical enough move and a typical Ruy Lopez device: By 
threatening axb5, White forces Black into a concession. -b4, weakening the light 
squares and the harmony of our pawn chain -Bb7, misplacing the bishop that will 
be staring at the e4-d3 block and failing to challenge the bishop on b3 via e6 
-Rb8, giving up the a-file that White can open at his pleasure.} Bb7 $5 
{Surprise! I have chosen door B. 8... b4 remains more popular at all levels, but 
I have reasons for going the other way. The main reason is I have a fresh idea 
in Bb7 that I'm excited about. The other is mild 8... b4 fatigue: With the 
explosion in popularity of both 8. a4 and the White concept that Be6 can be met 
by Bxe6 fighting against the doubled e-pawns, the theory has become giant here 
and it has become a mildly sad fight for equality in both 9. d4 and 9. a5 
followed by d3. Still very playable, although personally I have never fully felt 
at ease with the positions after 9. a5 d6 10. d3 Be6 11. Bxe6, that requires a 
positional understanding way above my pay grade. So, let me introduce you to the 
wonderful world of 8... Bb7! For starters, we parry the threat of axb5 and keep 
our options open with the d-pawn.} 9. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4][%csl Re4,Rb7] By far the 
best and most challenging move. White cripples the b7-bishop and makes sure 
...d5 won't have the desired impact. On the downside, he gives up the dream of 
c3-d4, therefore putting less pressure on Black's position.} d6 {Reality bites, 
we need to play it safe. 10...Re8 was used by some pretty strong players, but I 
do not trust it. 10... d5 doesn't work. After d6, White has a choice.} 10. Nbd2 
{The mainline. White prepares the usual Nf1-Ng3 without touching his c-pawn 
yet.} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5b3][%csl Rb3] This is the move that attracted me to 
revisit 8... Bb7. Black plans to go Nc5. The move got a shaky rep after Topalov 
got into trouble with it against Kasparov in 2004. I don't think the opening was 
to blame though - and apparently neither does Topalov, as he just repeated 10... 
Nd7 in 2019 vs Nakamura.} 11. c3 Nc5 12. Bc2 $6 {This is the line we are hoping 
for.} Nxa4 $1 {Of course, we grab the 2 bishops.} 13. Bxa4 bxa4 14. Qxa4 Kh8 $1 
{[%cal Gf7f5,Gb7f3][%csl Rf3] The announcement that f5 is coming and that our 
caterpillar on b7 can become a beautiful butterfly after all.} 15. Nf1 f5 $40 *

