1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. 
a4 {We meet another member of the trifecta of evil trying to undermine our faith 
in the Marshall. 8. c3 followed by 12. d3 and 6. d3 are the other members of 
that club. 8. a4 is a logical enough move and a typical Ruy Lopez device: By 
threatening axb5, White forces Black into a concession. -b4, weakening the light 
squares and the harmony of our pawn chain -Bb7, misplacing the bishop that will 
be staring at the e4-d3 block and failing to challenge the bishop on b3 via e6 
-Rb8, giving up the a-file that White can open at his pleasure.} Bb7 $5 
{Surprise! I have chosen door B. 8... b4 remains more popular at all levels, but 
I have reasons for going the other way. The main reason is I have a fresh idea 
in Bb7 that I'm excited about. The other is mild 8... b4 fatigue: With the 
explosion in popularity of both 8. a4 and the White concept that Be6 can be met 
by Bxe6 fighting against the doubled e-pawns, the theory has become giant here 
and it has become a mildly sad fight for equality in both 9. d4 and 9. a5 
followed by d3. Still very playable, although personally I have never fully felt 
at ease with the positions after 9. a5 d6 10. d3 Be6 11. Bxe6, that requires a 
positional understanding way above my pay grade. So, let me introduce you to the 
wonderful world of 8... Bb7! For starters, we parry the threat of axb5 and keep 
our options open with the d-pawn.} 9. d3 {By far the best and most challenging 
move. White cripples the b7-bishop and makes sure ...d5 won't have the desired 
impact. On the downside, he gives up the dream of c3-d4, therefore putting less 
pressure on Black's position.} d6 {Reality bites, we need to play it safe. 
10...Re8 was used by some pretty strong players, but I do not trust it. 10... d5 
doesn't work. After d6, White has a choice.} 10. Nbd2 {The mainline. White 
prepares the usual Nf1-Ng3 without touching his c-pawn yet.} Nd7 $1 {This is the 
move that attracted me to revisit 8... Bb7. Black plans to go Nc5. The move got 
a shaky rep after Topalov got into trouble with it against Kasparov in 2004. I 
don't think the opening was to blame though - and apparently neither does 
Topalov, as he just repeated 10... Nd7 in 2019 vs Nakamura.} 11. c3 Nc5 12. axb5 
axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Bc2 {The real starting point. White has managed to keep 
his bishop and is getting ready for some good old Spanish torture, Nf1-N (e) g3, 
d4, all that stuff. However, we have already exchanged one pawn on the queenside 
and Black rushes to trade another one. With 6 pawns left, not only will the 
combat zone be smaller and easier to defend, Black can even use the empty space 
on the queenside to activate his pieces and distract White form focusing on an 
attack.} b4 $1 15. Nf1 Qa2 $1 {[%cal Bb4b3,Rb3c2][%csl Rc2] The threat of b3 is 
a bit awkward to meet...} *

