axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Bc2 {The real starting point. White has managed to keep 
his bishop and is getting ready for some good old Spanish torture, Nf1-N (e) g3, 
d4, all that stuff. However, we have already exchanged one pawn on the queenside 
and Black rushes to trade another one. With 6 pawns left, not only will the 
combat zone be smaller and easier to defend, Black can even use the empty space 
on the queenside to activate his pieces and distract White form focusing on an 
attack.} b4 $1 15. d4 bxc3 16. bxc3 Nd7 {Back to base. The mission has been 
accomplished though, all queenside pawns are gone.} 17. Nf1 Qa1 $1 {This is my 
improvement over that old Kasparov-Topalov game. We keep White busy with his 
c3-pawn. Note that Topalov himself still seems to like 17... Bf6.} 18. Ne3 {The 
critical move, daring Black to take the pawn.} Bf6 $1 {No thank you. Now that 
White committed to Ne3, Bf6 is fine.} 19. d5 Ncb8 {This time, we go backward.} 
20. Bd2 Qxd1 {Generally, we will accept queen exchanges in all these lines. The 
endgames do not hold too many terrors.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish 6. d3 #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825638"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 
{[%cal Bc6a5,Ga5b3][%csl Rb3] This humble looking-move has tirelessly worked his 
way up to the top of the list of threats to the Marshall/1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6. 
Credit goes to Vishy Anand, who was the first to consistently use it at the 
highest level, starting in 2007. No, a3 does not threaten anything. It stops the 
b3-bishop from being captured by Na5 and ensures it will stay on the a2-g8 
diagonal, where it is a powerhouse. The only way to get rid of it will be 
...Be6, which comes with its own problems (accepting doubled pawns could be one) 
. Opposed to a4, White does not have to worried about the weakness of the 
b4-square or a potential bxa4 by Black after the bishop went to a2. c3 is the 
other common way to preserve the bishop, but a) c2 is a more passive square than 
a2 b) there is no Nc3! Nc3 is a big part of White's plan in a3 lines, a rare 
sight for Ruy Lopezes. I have studied a lot of lines against this a3 stuff over 
the years. It did feature heavily in the Karjakin-Carlsen match, amongst other 
things. I have revisited my old notes on the different systems with modern 
engines (Leela!) and concluded that practice is right: The mainline is the 
mainline for a reason. We will get to meet it in a minute. For us, this means 
bad news (no surprise value, quite some stuff to grasp) and good news (stuff be 
OK) . My obsession with this line might be a bit of spacebar-nerd/top tournament 
watcher filter-bubble. I do not think you will face it that often. I'll still 
tell you about it.} Na5 {This is an important alternative. Black delays castling 
for now. It might be easier to learn than our main lines, so I would urge you to 
consider it too.} 9. Ba2 c5 {Going for the Chigorin setup before castling.} 10. 
Nc3 Be6 {This is Peter Svidler's pet line. There have been new developments 
here. I used to consider it to be too risky, but now see it as a valid 
alternative to our main lines.} 11. Bg5 O-O {Transposes to territory we know. No 
worries here.} *

