[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825639"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 
{This humble looking-move has tirelessly worked his way up to the top of the 
list of threats to the Marshall/1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6. Credit goes to Vishy Anand, 
who was the first to consistently use it at the highest level, starting in 2007. 
No, a3 does not threaten anything. It stops the b3-bishop from being captured by 
Na5 and ensures it will stay on the a2-g8 diagonal, where it is a powerhouse. 
The only way to get rid of it will be ...Be6, which comes with its own problems 
(accepting doubled pawns could be one) . Opposed to a4, White does not have to 
worried about the weakness of the b4-square or a potential bxa4 by Black after 
the bishop went to a2. c3 is the other common way to preserve the bishop, but a) 
c2 is a more passive square than a2 b) there is no Nc3! Nc3 is a big part of 
White's plan in a3 lines, a rare sight for Ruy Lopezes. I have studied a lot of 
lines against this a3 stuff over the years. It did feature heavily in the 
Karjakin-Carlsen match, amongst other things. I have revisited my old notes on 
the different systems with modern engines (Leela!) and concluded that practice 
is right: The mainline is the mainline for a reason. We will get to meet it in a 
minute. For us, this means bad news (no surprise value, quite some stuff to 
grasp) and good news (stuff be OK) . My obsession with this line might be a bit 
of spacebar-nerd/top tournament watcher filter-bubble. I do not think you will 
face it that often. I'll still tell you about it.} Na5 {This is an important 
alternative. Black delays castling for now. It might be easier to learn than our 
main lines, so I would urge you to consider it too.} 9. Ba2 c5 {Going for the 
Chigorin setup before castling.} 10. Nc3 Be6 {This is Peter Svidler's pet line. 
There have been new developments here. I used to consider it to be too risky, 
but now see it as a valid alternative to our main lines.} 11. Nh4 $1 {[%cal 
Bh4f5] By far the critical test. Slow moves justify Black's move order with the 
delayed O-O.} O-O 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 d5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge5] This is the 
big new idea, first employed by Harikrishna vs. Karjakin in 2019. Black builds 
an impressive pawn center and does not give up on the d5 square. Both his d5 and 
e5 pawns will be targets for the white pieces, so he will have to use tactical 
means to hold that center. The good news is they seem to work.} 14. Bg5 c4 $1 
{Keeping the bishop boxed in on a2 is the goal. White has a lot of tries now 
that require specific responses.} 15. Qe2 Nc6 $1 {Using the fact that Nd4 might 
come with tempo.} 16. Rad1 h6 $1 {Looks like a loss of time, but Black has a 
specific trick in mind.} 17. Bxf6 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e2,Bd4c2][%csl Rc2] The 
point! The knight lands on d4 before White can go dxc4 to give the rook access 
to that horsey.} 18. Qxe5 Bxf6 19. Qxd5 Ne2+ $1 20. Kh1 Bxc3 21. Qxd8 Rfxd8 22. 
bxc3 Nxc3 23. Ra1 cxd3 {[%cal Bd8d3] And Black wins (for once)!} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Two Knights (Ng5) #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825631"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7][%csl Rf7] Direct 
play. The knight teams up with the bishop to attack the f7-pawn. It has always 
remained topical and you might meet it every now and then against White players 
looking for fun irrational positions. Theoretically, Black is in good shape 
currently, the resulting positions are at least as risky for White as they are 
for Black. Oh, we will be a pawn down most of the time, but I'm sure you guys 
are used to that by now.} d5 {[%cal Rc4f7] The only good move - we can't allow 
anything to land on f7.} 5. exd5 Na5 $1 {Once again the only good move, but this 
one is is a bit more surprising. Going to the rim and all that. The good news is 
we keep attacking the white pieces with every move, distracting him from 
developing} 6. Bb5+ {The only good move, the bishop goes away with tempo. Or at 
least with check.} c6 {Continuing our policy to attack them white pieces. Tempi 
over structure is the motto here.} 7. dxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gc6b5] Same policy. Nxc6 
is a bit slow. White faces a choice where to go with his bishop now. Play will 
be quite different depending on his choice. We are, however, a pawn down with a 
knight on the rim and a wrecked structure, therefore I am surprised at just how 
healthy the black position is. But it is, his central control and lead 
development ensure good chances everywhere. Let's explore!} 8. Qf3 {Not a move I 
would expect to see often. There is some logic to the idea that we should not 
develop the queen too early, so it doesn't get tossed around too much. Other 
than that, Black has at least 3 good replies.} h6 $1 {A fresh move that might 
catch some people off-guard. There is nothing wrong with either... Be7 or cxb5!? 
Qxa8 Qc7 either.} 9. Ne4 cxb5 $1 {The real surprise. We are giving an exchange 
on a8.} 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 {The queen has other things to do. Even the opening of 
the g-file will come in handy.} 11. Qxa8 Qd7 $1 {Strictly the only move. Black 
wants to go Nc6, locking the queen up.} 12. b4 {A funny computer move. The point 
is to go a4 without allowing Black to reply with b4.} Nc6 {[%csl Ra8]} 13. a4 
Nd4 {[%cal Bd4c2] OK, the locking up didn't go according to plan. Off to a new 
mission!} 14. O-O Rg8 {[%cal Gg8g2] OK, it's a mess. Plans include Ke7 to unpin 
the bishop followed by Bb7.} 15. axb5 Nf3+ $3 {Another only move, but a pretty 
nice touch.} 16. Qxf3 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7g2,Bg8g2][%csl Rg2]} *

