1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 {Direct play. The knight teams up with 
the bishop to attack the f7-pawn. It has always remained topical and you might 
meet it every now and then against White players looking for fun irrational 
positions. Theoretically, Black is in good shape currently, the resulting 
positions are at least as risky for White as they are for Black. Oh, we will be 
a pawn down most of the time, but I'm sure you guys are used to that by now.} d5 
{The only good move - we can't allow anything to land on f7.} 5. exd5 Na5 $1 
{Once again the only good move, but this one is is a bit more surprising. Going 
to the rim and all that. The good news is we keep attacking the white pieces 
with every move, distracting him from developing} 6. Bb5+ {The only good move, 
the bishop goes away with tempo. Or at least with check.} c6 {Continuing our 
policy to attack them white pieces. Tempi over structure is the motto here.} 7. 
dxc6 bxc6 {Same policy. Nxc6 is a bit slow. White faces a choice where to go 
with his bishop now. Play will be quite different depending on his choice. We 
are, however, a pawn down with a knight on the rim and a wrecked structure, 
therefore I am surprised at just how healthy the black position is. But it is, 
his central control and lead development ensure good chances everywhere. Let's 
explore!} 8. Bd3 {I would think this move is slightly more popular than 8. Be2 
nowadays. The bishop controls e4, making sure White can retreat his knight there 
is questioned. The obvious drawback Bd3 has is that it's tough to move the 
d-pawn now, making queenside development far from straightforward.} Nd5 {We're 
going with the mainline here. The knight centralizes, and eyes f4. Black also 
threatens Qxg5, while the road for the f-pawn is cleared. Ng4 is a fun 
alternative recently play by Grischuk, but it seems to lead to some strange 
ending I didn't like that much. So let's get our own strange ending via Nd5.} 9. 
h4 {This looks a bit strange, but it does defend the knight.} h6 {[%cal 
Gh6g5][%csl Rg5] Logical, but opening a Pandora's Box of tactics. In general, 
Black should be ready for some irrational stuff after 3... Nf6, if all these 
positional are not to your liking, 3... Bc5 is your move.} 10. Qh5 Qf6 $1 11. 
Nxf7 Nf4 $1 {[%cal Gf4d3,Gf4h5][%csl Rh5,Rd3] Geometry!} 12. Nd6+ Kd7 {[%csl 
Rd6,Rd3,Rh5] Wins!} *

