[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825627"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 a6 {[%cal Gc5a7] I generally 
prefer going a6 before d6, as it cuts out white plans with (...d6) b4 Bb6 a4.} 
6. O-O d6 {One general thing about move-orders: In the Italian there are lots. I 
will not list every single transposition there is but trust you guys to figure 
some out. Black goes a6, d6, Ba7, O-O, h6 and Re8, usually in that order. White 
mainly goes d3, c3, O-O, a4, Re1, Nbd2 h3, but he can do so via different 
orders. I hope the confusion will be minimal, but please keep your angry emails 
'why didn't you cover 7. Re1, it is a mainline' in the drafts folder until you 
are sure the line you are missing is really not covered in the main course. 
Sorry, I find all these move-orders very upsetting too!} 7. a4 {Grabbing space.} 
Ba7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 h6 {[%cal Gh6g5][%csl Gg5]} 10. Nbd2 Re8 11. b4 Be6 {[%cal 
Ge8e6,Be6c4][%csl Ge6] This is where the real action starts. This position is 
explored in a lot of detail in the larger course.} *

