[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825635"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {The Scotch. Instead of the slow battles that White 
seeks in the Spanish or Italian, in the Scotch White immediate changes the 
situation in the center, forcing the exchange of his d-pawn for the black 
e-pawn. That will give White greater center control (the pawn on e4 versus the 
pawn on d7), but there is a price to pay: White is no longer the side with a 
lead in development, as he will move his knight twice in the first four moves. 
In many ways, that determines the battles to come: White wants to consolidate 
his better structure/spacial advantage, while Black should try to play 
dynamically, developing quickly and asking questions. From an opening theory 
standpoint, the Scotch is far less scary than the Spanish or the Italian. It 
still pops up in top-level chess, but mostly as a surprise weapon (just like 
Kasparov undusted it in 1990 to spring it on Karpov). Black is fine, but 
especially in the (critical) lines I will be recommending. The positions are far 
from typical, the pawn structure, in particular, being nothing that we are used 
to. Therefore, it pays off to check the lines in the main course quite a bit, as 
play is often quite tactical/move-by-move, so relying on common sense and 
pattern recognition is sometimes not as helpful here.} exd4 {The only decent 
move.} 4. Nxd4 {White just recaptures the pawn.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4] 
This move has been my weapon of choice for a long time now. Black develops the 
knight and attacks the pawn on e4, what could be more natural?} 5. Nxc6 {The 
knight moves for the third time, exchanging his colleague while doubling the 
black pawns. White could still chicken out from the sharp battles that often 
follow by going 5. Nc3, transposing back to the much calmer Four Knights.} bxc6 
{This is not a tough decision as the alternative dxc6 just leads to a thankless 
endgame with a bad structure.} 6. e5 {[%csl Rf6] A critical, but also risky 
move. White tries to push the knight around, but Black has other ideas. 6. e5 
also marks the point of no return, now the game will get properly strange. In 
Nc3 or Bd3, White still had calmer options.} Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e1][%csl Re5,Re1] 
Pinning the pawn. This move looks awkward, but it also forces White into an 
awkward reply. Black will argue that Qe2 is more hurtful for White than Qe7 is 
for him.} 7. Qe2 {As forced as Qe7.} Nd5 {[%cal Bg7g6,Bf8g7,Gg7e5,Ge7e5][%csl 
Re5] The knight was back under attack and very much has to move. Black wants to 
follow up with g6-Bg7 more often than not, developing his bishop while attacking 
the pawn on e5. One key question Black has to answer is how he wants to react to 
8. c4, intending to chase his knight around further.} 8. c4 {The mainline by 
far. Quo vadis, horsey?} Ba6 $5 {[%cal Ga6e2] We shall not retreat! The bishop 
pins the c-pawn while developing, admittedly to a shaky square. Ba6 has served 
me well over the years, never making me feel the need to investigate the 
alternative 8... Nb6.} 9. Nd2 {The trendiest move and the one posing the biggest 
theoretical problems.} g6 $1 {Kramnik to the rescue! I had concluded that we 
cannot get away with this move for a while and sought shelter in the 
alternatives 9... f6 or 9... O-O-O. Both these moves are acceptable, but it 
turns out that my fears about going g6 here were greatly exaggerated.} 10. Nf3 
{[%cal Bc1g5] This is the white idea, the knight covers e5 and prepares Bg5. 
There is a price to pay for this fluent development, however. Black has a little 
check.} Qb4+ $1 {[%cal Gb4b2,Gb4c4,Gb4e1][%csl Rb2,Re1,Rc4] Forcing the white 
king to stay in the center.} 11. Kd1 $1 {The only move. Try the alternatives... 
This position has been a tricky puzzle for years, and I have changed my mind 
about the way to go here more than once: From Rb8 to Bg7 to Nb6 to our choice. 
Sure, it might change again, but I am currently pretty confident that our next 
move closes this line.} Ne7 {[%cal Bc6c5,Be7c6] Voluntarily retreating and not 
even attacking anything, but showing good understanding (and good engines) The 
knight wants to be rerouted to c6 after ...c5, and this is the move that solves 
all our problems.} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Bh4h5] The best try and not surprisingly the 
move favored by Leela0. We face the eternal question of how to react to a white 
h-pawn launch.} h6 {[%cal Bh4h5,Bg6g5] This is an interesting option too, 
intending to meet h5 with g5.} 13. Kc2 Bg7 14. Bd2 Qb6 {[%cal Bc6c5,Be7c6,Be8c8] 
We will keep queens on the board, go c5, often O-O-O and maybe even ...d5 later, 
with good prospects.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scotch Four Knights #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825636"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 {[%cal 
Gf6e4,Gb4e1][%csl Re4] By far the main move. Pinning, developing, preparing to 
castle.} 6. Nxc6 {The only decent move.} bxc6 7. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4][%csl Ge4]} d5 
{[%csl Re4]} 8. exd5 O-O $5 {Gambitting the pawn just for show. cxd5 usually 
transposes back.} 9. O-O Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rf2f3,Gg4d1][%csl Rd1] Avoiding the dull 
cxd5 positions. Introduced by the strong Indian theoretician Vidit against Wei 
Yi in 2018. The only problem is Black still doesn't have great winning chances. 
Modern chess! But we can ask some questions, at least.} 10. f3 {The most 
critical move.} Bh5 {[%csl Rf2,Rg1] Black has weakened the dark squares around 
the white king.} 11. Bg5 {Developing quickly, though now Black wins some 
material back.} Qd6 {[%cal Gd6c6,Gd6c5,Gd6f6] I have been convinced that this is 
the best move after all, following Yu-Mamedyarov.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Ne4 Qxb2 
14. dxc6 Qe5 $1 {[%cal Bf7f5,Ge5c5,Gc5c6][%csl Re4,Rc6] And Black is OK, e.g.} 
15. Rb1 a5 16. Qe2 f5 17. Ng5 Qf6 18. Qe6+ Kh8 19. Qxf6 Rxf6 {[%cal Bf6c6] 
Eventually regaining the pawn.} *

