[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Danish Gambit"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825622"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. d4 {The Center game. Not the most logical move as White is not 
yet prepared to recapture on d4 with a minor piece, but I am sure it has its 
fans - both in the Gambit- and in the Bring Out the Queen on Move 3 community.} 
exd4 {3 points for guessing that one.} 3. c3 (3. Qxd4 {is of course also covered 
in the main course.}) Qe7 $5 {[%cal Ge7e1][%csl Re4] A very greedy move. Of 
course, 3... d5 is perfectly fine, but we might as well try to refute White's 
play while we're here. Is it usually a good idea to bring the queen out 
pawn-hunting? No. Does it work here? Yes.} 4. cxd4 {The best try.} Qxe4+ {This 
was the plan.} 5. Be3 Nf6 {[%cal Bf8b4] We are done with the pawngrabbing, let's 
start the developing!} 6. Nc3 Bb4 {More developing.} 7. Nf3 Nd5 $5 {[%cal 
Bd5e3][%csl Re3] OK, enough with this developing stuff, time to break some rules 
again. This time the point is to exchange the knight for the bishop, bothering 
White along the way.} 8. Qd2 Nxe3 9. fxe3 {[%cal Bc3e4][%csl Re4]} Qe7 {Nxe4 was 
a threat now!} 10. Bd3 d5 {[%cal Gd5e4][%csl Ge4,Gd5] A somewhat risky move, as 
we are behind in development due to our early queen adventures and d5 gives 
White a chance to go for a quick e4, opening the position. But we are in time.} 
11. O-O Nd7 $1 {[%cal Bd7f6,Gf6e4][%csl Ge4] Heading for f6.} 12. Rae1 Nf6 13. 
e4 {What else?} dxe4 {Yeah, it looks a bit scary.} 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 $1 {The only 
move.} 15. Rxe4 Be6 {[%cal Be8c8,Be8g8] The only move!} 16. Qe3 c6 $1 {[%cal 
Gc6b5,Gc6d5] Taking a time out to stop d5 and Nd5.} 17. Ng5 {[%cal 
Ge3e6,Gg5e6][%csl Re6]} O-O $15 {[%csl Rd4] White had to work hard to regain 
that pawn on e6, but all he will get from it will be a worse position with a 
weak d4-pawn.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The King's Gambit #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825623"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. f4 {The King's Gambit! Of course, we will give this majestic 
opening the respectful treatment it deserves due to its rich history. On pure 
chess grounds, I am not sure it really had to be included in the series. Here is 
a list of moves I consider to be stronger than 2. f4: • 2. Qf3 • 2. Qe2 • 
2. Ne2 • 2. b3 • 2. a4 • 2. h3 • 2. Bb5 • 2. Be2 • 2. Bd3 None of 
those will get much airtime. Think I'm exaggerating? Leela0 currently considers 
2. f4 the 21st best move after 1. e4 e5, but it keeps going back and forth 
between 2. f4 and 2. Qg4. Anyway, 2. f4: White fights for the center by trying 
to lure the black pawn from e5 away from the d4 square. In an ideal world, White 
would then go Nf3, d4, Nc3, Bc4, recapture the pawn on f4 and launch a 
devastating attack against f7/the black king. Nope, not going to happen. 2. f4 
gives a pawn and weakens the white king without a lot of tempi to show for it. I 
am torn about the best third move for Black, but it is a pleasant choice.} exf4 
3. Nf3 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Bd7d5][%csl Re4] This sober reply should take a lot 
of fun out of White's gambiteering. We develop a piece, attack the e4 pawn and 
get ready to jump to h5 to support our f4 pawn if questioned. Stockfish giving 
this as the main move has made its popularity skyrocket, and I have indeed seen 
it recommended plenty by now. For good reason - it's a good move. Frankly, I 
have very little to add to Ivan Salgado's coverage in his Kindle e-book 'The End 
of the King's Gambit?', which I can recommend to all of you that are looking for 
even more meat on this bone. I've gone Vegan, millennial-style, do I still use 
meat on the bone? Or is it time to adjust to 'feeding two birds with one scone' 
and all that? TLDR: King's Gambit bad, Nf6 good.} 4. e5 Nh5 $1 {[%cal 
Gh5f4][%csl Gf4] A knight on the rim protects our extra pawn. As they say.} 5. 
d4 d6 $5 {[%cal Gd8h4,Bd6e5] I have to admit I find this move a little 
counterintuitive. We open the position, going for a direct infight. I guess it's 
good because it works? The fact that the white king is vulnerable to a check 
from h4 (after Nxe5) is certainly relevant here.} 6. Qe2 {This somewhat clumsy 
move can lead to funky complications - if Black feels like. It is not too late 
to keep the center closed with d5, keeping a pleasant position. But we might as 
well!} dxe5 $5 {Leading to sick complications. Black comes out on top, but what 
a mess it is.} 7. Nxe5 Qh4+ {[%cal Gh5g3][%csl Re1] Without fear of discovered 
checks! We are still following Salgado's analysis here.} 8. g3 Nxg3 {A fork!} 9. 
hxg3 Qxh1 {surprisingly White has no way to capitalize on our queen stuck in the 
corner and being allowed to give a discovered check.} 10. Ng6+ Be6 $1 11. Nxh8 
Nc6 $19 {[%cal Be8c8,Gc6d4,Gf4g3][%csl Rh8,Rg3,Rd4] The knight on h8 is doomed, 
O-O-O will come, fxg3 is a threat, so is Nxd4. Black is winning.} *

