[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The King's Gambit #2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825624"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. f4 {The King's Gambit! Of course, we will give this majestic 
opening the respectful treatment it deserves due to its rich history. On pure 
chess grounds, I am not sure it really had to be included in the series. Here is 
a list of moves I consider to be stronger than 2. f4: • 2. Qf3 • 2. Qe2 • 
2. Ne2 • 2. b3 • 2. a4 • 2. h3 • 2. Bb5 • 2. Be2 • 2. Bd3 None of 
those will get much airtime. Think I'm exaggerating? Leela0 currently considers 
2. f4 the 21st best move after 1. e4 e5, but it keeps going back and forth 
between 2. f4 and 2. Qg4. Anyway, 2. f4: White fights for the center by trying 
to lure the black pawn from e5 away from the d4 square. In an ideal world, White 
would then go Nf3, d4, Nc3, Bc4, recapture the pawn on f4 and launch a 
devastating attack against f7/the black king. Nope, not going to happen. 2. f4 
gives a pawn and weakens the white king without a lot of tempi to show for it. I 
am torn about the best third move for Black, but it is a pleasant choice.} exf4 
3. Nf3 Nf6 $1 {This sober reply should take a lot of fun out of White's 
gambiteering. We develop a piece, attack the e4 pawn and get ready to jump to h5 
to support our f4 pawn if questioned. Stockfish giving this as the main move has 
made its popularity skyrocket, and I have indeed seen it recommended plenty by 
now. For good reason - good move. Frankly, I have very little to add to Ivan 
Salgado's coverage in his Kindle e-book 'The End of the King's Gambit?', which I 
can recommend to all of you that are looking for even more meat on this bone. 
I've gone Vegan, millennial-style, do I still use meat on the bone? Or is it 
time to adjust to 'feeding two birds with one scone' and all that? TLDR: King's 
Gambit bad, Nf6 good} 4. e5 Nh5 $1 {A knight on the rim protects our extra pawn. 
As they say.} 5. d4 d6 $5 {I have to admit I find this move a little 
counterintuitive. We open the position, going for a direct infight. I guess it's 
good because it works? The fact that the white king is vulnerable to a check 
from h4 (after Nxe5) is certainly relevant here.} 6. Qe2 {This somewhat clumsy 
move can lead to funky complications - if Black feels like. It is not too late 
to keep the center closed with d5, keeping a pleasant position. But we might as 
well!} dxe5 $5 {Leading to sick complications. Black comes out on top, but what 
a mess it is.} 7. Nxe5 Qh4+ {Without fear of discovered checks! We are still 
following Salgado's analysis here.} 8. g3 Nxg3 {A fork!} 9. hxg3 Qxh1 
{Surprisingly White has no way to capitalize on our queen stuck in the corner 
and being allowed to give a discovered check.} 10. Bxf4 {Curb Your Enthusiasm.} 
Bd6 $146 {[%cal Gd6f4,Be8g8] A sick move, inviting the discovered check. Darn 
you, computers! Still following my boy Salgado here. Then again, it is the first 
Stockfish and Leela line, so I don't feel too guilty.} 11. Nc3 {White's best bet 
is to go for quick O-O-O.} O-O {Haha, safe and you didn't even give a check!} 
12. O-O-O Bh3 $1 {[%cal Bh3f1] Now that the king is safe, it's time to save the 
queen too.} 13. Nxf7 Bxf4+ 14. gxf4 Nd7 $1 15. Qc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] This looks 
scary but Black can take the knight now.} Rxf7 16. Qxf7+ Kxf7 17. Bc4+ {[%cal 
Bd1h1][%csl Rh1]} Be6 18. Bxe6+ Kxe6 19. Rxh1 Nf6 {[%cal Gh7h2,Ba8d8][%csl 
Ge6,Rd4,Rf4,Gh7] Is this what the King's Gambit comes down to? An endgame with 
equal material where Black has good winning chances? Passed h-pawn, f4 is weak, 
our king is more active. Let's face it, this will never happen in your games (or 
mine), but it's still fascinating it comes down to this with apparent best 
play.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Site "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Bishop's Game #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-jan-gustafssons-1-e4-e5/course/31256, variation/5825625"]

1. e4 e5 {This is how we do it! We shall cover all the good, bad and ugly 
choices White has after this. The following is just a sneak preview into some of 
the lines.} 2. Bc4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4] An obvious enough start.} 3. d3 
Nc6 {Go 4. Nf3 kind sir, let us play a Giuoco (seriously, playing the lottery 
has better odds than getting IUO in the right order in Guioco) Pianissimo!} 4. 
Nc3 {The main try for stubborn independence. White refuses to go Nf3, therefore 
keeping his f-pawn free to advance.} Bc5 $5 {[%cal Bd7d6] This might look like 
the most natural move in the world (and it is!) but it is still one of my more 
offbeat recommendations. Conventional wisdom teaches us to choose between 4... 
Bb4 and 4... Na5 here. Both fine moves, but let me briefly share my reasons for 
not going with them. I like the stupidity of going for both Nc6 and Bc5 here, as 
we are supposed to choose one. Nope!} 5. f4 {The refutation, but I am not buying 
it. White goes for a sort of King's Gambit declined position, usually seen via 
2. f4 Bc5? 3. Nf3 d6 4. Nc3 Nc6 etc.} d6 6. Nf3 exf4 $1 {intending to play as 
stupidly as possible. You want us to open the half-open f-file and then castle 
into an attack while you control the center? As you wish, sir!} 7. Bxf4 O-O 
{[%cal Gc5g1,Bc8e6] It turns out matters are not so simple. White cannot castle 
kingside, so he should opt for the queenside, but Black will ask a question in 
the form of Be6 along the way. I am aware our play looks strange. But I did 
check this position quite a bit and could not find any white edge.} 8. Qd2 Be6 
9. Bb3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4][%csl Rb3] far from the only move, but preparing a 
welcome committee on the queenside makes a lot of sense.} 10. Bg5 {This is 
always a question in these positions, but once again Black has an answer.} h6 
{[%csl Rg5]} 11. Bh4 Nd4 {[%cal Bf6e4,Gd8h4][%csl Rh4] And the nasty threat of 
Nxe4!! breaks the pin.} 12. O-O-O Nxe4 $15 {[%cal Ge4d2,Bd4f3,Gd8h4][%csl 
Rh4,Rf3,Rd2] Remember this motif!} *

